ya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Poyle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Pulley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pulley","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>Pulleis</i> ‘man from Apulia’, a country in Italy, named in the Middle English as <i>Poille</i>, <i>Poyle</i>, <i>Apuelle</i>.","English: habitational name from Pulley in Shropshire.","Possibly also an Americanized form of German <b>Puley</b>: from the medieval personal name <i>Pelagius</i> (from Greek <i>pelagos</i> ‘sea’), the name of a Christian martyr."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John de la Poyle was born about 1273, in Hampton Poyle, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Walter de la Poyle, was 24 and his mother, Alice de Hampton, was 22. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Mabilla or Mabel. He died in 1318, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 46."},"et":{"about 1273–1318":"umbes 1273–1318","1273–1318":"1273–1318","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1303–1332":"1303–1332","1306–Male":"1306–Surnud","1310–1359":"1310–1359","1318–1337":"1318–1337","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1252–1317":"1252–1317","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","Abt 1274":"umbes 1274","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1303":"1303","after 1317":"pärast 1317","about 1306":"umbes 1306","about 1303":"umbes 1303","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","1298":"1298","about 1310":"umbes 1310","about 1273":"umbes 1273","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Guildford, Surrey, England":"Guildford, Surrey, Inglismaa